	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>l_oliveira</b> [ Tue Oct 09, 2012 5:35 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Tales of Phantasia 2x29f032</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Actually, LO-ROM means the rom is connected to the bus with address line A15 from the CPU skipped.<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Super_NES_Programming/SNES_memory_map">http://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Super_NES_ ... memory_map</a><!-- m --><br /><br />Because the designer can do anything what he want with the chips on the cartridge by just changing how it's connected it's possible to have multiple modes on a single cart.<br /><br />But now, answering your question, if you're using a ToP cart as donor, you already have the correct circuit on the board. So it should just work.<br /><br /><br />When I made my cart I used three 27C160 chips connected in 8 bit mode so I just split the ROM into 3 16Mbit files (2MB). I also had to rewire the circuit a few times until I figured out what would make it work.<br /><br />Upper and Lower usually refer to the 1st half and 2nd half of the game. On the particular case of ToP you're obligated to use two ROM chips as they're connected differently. The other solution would require a complex logic circuit to change the way the ROM is connected to the SNES while the game is running, based on where the SNES want to read the ROM. Too complex, not worth the hassle.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
